prism

Class TileList

  • java.lang.Object
    • prism.TileList

  • public class TileList
extends java.lang.Object
    This class represent a list of tiles which have corners in Pareto points, and which represent an under-approximation of the Pareto curve.

    • Field Detail

      • tolerance

        private double tolerance
        Threshold for approximation of the Pareto curve.

      • opsAndBoundsList

        private OpsAndBoundsList opsAndBoundsList
        This is used when printing the tileList to the user. The information we need are whether the reward is min (to multiply by -1) and whether the probability is min (to do 1-value)

      • storedTileLists

        protected static java.util.List<TileList> storedTileLists
        This is where a TileLists are stored to be later retrieved in GUI. It is a workaround for the fact that Pareto curve can't be returned in any reasonable way. To ensure correct concurrent behaviour, object accessing any stored tile lists or elements should synchronise on this object;

      • storedFormulasX

        protected static java.util.List<Expression> storedFormulasX
        Formulas for X and Y axes (or multi-obj formulas) of the corresponding elements of storedTileLists.

      • getCandidateHyperplane

        public Point getCandidateHyperplane()
        Returns a weight vector which could yield a new Pareto point when used. null is returned if no candidate point exists. TODO: currently just calls another method.

      • getFreshRealCandidateHyperplane

        private Point getFreshRealCandidateHyperplane()
        Queries the tiles of this TileList to get a new weight vector which could yield a new pareto point when used. null is returned if no candidate point exists. It gives absolute preference to weight vectors having zero in one of the coordinates.

      • getNumberOfDifferentPoints

        public int getNumberOfDifferentPoints()
        Returns the number of different points that form the tiles of this TileList. The implementation is rather inefficient and is intended only for debugging purposes.

      • getPoints

        public java.util.List<Point> getPoints()
        Returns the points that form the tiles of this TileList. The implementation is rather inefficient and is intended only for debugging purposes.

      • getPointsWithoutCovered

        public java.util.List<Point> getPointsWithoutCovered()
        Returns the points that form the tiles of this TileList, omitting the points that are covered by other points. The implementation is rather inefficient and is intended only for debugging purposes.

      • getRealPoints

        public java.util.List<Point> getRealPoints()
        Returns the points that form the actual Pareto curve (modifying the points from tiles according to the operator bound changes). The implementation is rather inefficient and is intended only for debugging purposes.

      • addNewPoint

        public void addNewPoint(Point point)
                 throws PrismException
        Adds a newly discovered point to this TileList. This basically means that some tiles will be split into smaller tiles. Also makes sure that the invariant "approximation is downward closed" is maintained true.
        Throws:
        PrismException

      • splitTilesByPoint

        protected void splitTilesByPoint(Point point,
                                 boolean isRealyFoundPoint)
                          throws PrismException
        Splits the Tiles using the new point. This basically means that some tiles will be replaced by smaller tiles. Note that this method does not check whether the tiles form a downward closed polyhedron, hence it shouldn't be called directly, but indirecly by calling addNewPoint(Point).
        Parameters:
        isRealyFoundPoint - False if point is just a projection of a point found.
        Throws:
        PrismException

      • getDimension

        public int getDimension()
        returns the dimension of the points in this TileList
